*Absolutely. If I were mentoring you as a junior developer, I'd tell you this:
*Don't try to learn everything at once. Learn Java by building things, and learn DSA by solving problems consistently. That's the path that has worked for many successful software engineers.
->Since you're starting from the basics, here's the roadmap I would recommend.
Phase 1: Build a Strong Java Foundation (3–4 weeks)
Don't just watch videos. Write code every day.
Learn in this order:
  1. Variables and Data Types
  2. Operators
  3. Input and Output
  4. if-else and switch
  5. Loops (for, while, do-while)
  6. Methods (Functions)
  7. Arrays
  8. Strings
  9. Object-Oriented Programming
     > Classes
     > Objects
     > Constructors
     > Inheritance
     > Polymorphism
     > Abstraction
     > Interfaces
  10. Exception Handling
  11. Collections
     > ArrayList
     > LinkedList
     > HashMap
     > HashSet
     > Queue
     > Stack
  12. File Handling
  13. Multithreading
  14. Java 8 Features
    > Lambda Expressions
    > Streams
    > Optional
*Practice rule
->For every topic:
    >Learn for 30–45 minutes.
    >Write 10–15 small programs.
    >Modify the programs yourself.
For example, after learning loops:
    >Multiplication table
    >Prime number
    >Armstrong number
    >Palindrome
    >Fibonacci
    >Pattern printing
->Don't copy code. Type everything yourself.
*Phase 2: Start DSA (2–3 months)
Most students make a mistake here. They start solving difficult problems immediately.
Instead, follow this order:
 1.Arrays
 2.Strings
 3.Recursion
 4.Searching
 5.Sorting
 6.Hashing
 7.Linked List
 8.Stack
 9.Queue
 10.Trees
 11.Binary Search Trees
 12.Heaps
 13.Graphs
 14.Dynamic Programming

*For every topic:
   >Learn the concept.
   >Solve 20–30 easy problems.
   >Then medium problems.
   >Finally, hard problems if needed.
*Phase 3: Learn SQL
  ->A Java developer almost always works with databases.
   Learn:
     1.SELECT
     2.WHERE
     3.GROUP BY
     4.HAVING
     5.JOINs
     6.Subqueries
     7.Views
     8.Indexes
     9.Normalization
#Practice on sample databases.#
*Phase 4: Learn Git and GitHub
You already created your GitHub account.
Now learn:
   >git init
   >git clone
   >git add
   >git commit
   >git push
   >git pull
   >Branches
   >Merge
*Upload every project you build.*
*Phase 5: Learn Backend Development
Study:
   >JDBC
   >Servlets
   >JSP (basic understanding)
   >Spring Framework
   >Spring Boot
   >REST APIs
   >Hibernate/JPA
   >MySQL
#Build small APIs before moving to larger projects.#
*Phase 6: Build Projects
 ->Projects teach you more than tutorials.
   Start with:
    >Student Management System
    >Library Management System
    >Employee Management System
    >Banking Application
    >E-commerce Application
    >LinkedIn Clone
    >Instagram Clone
**Daily Routine (3–4 hours)
->1 hour: Java concepts
->1 hour: DSA practice
->1 hour: Project development
->30 minutes: Revise what you learned
#Even 2–3 focused hours every day will lead to strong progress over time.#
*How to solve DSA problems
   Whenever you solve a problem:
     1.Understand the problem.
     2.Solve it on paper.
     3.Write the algorithm.
     4.Write the Java code.
     5.Test it with different inputs.
     6.Optimize it.
     7.Learn its time complexity.
*Resources I recommend
    ->Visual Studio Code or IntelliJ IDEA for coding
    ->Git + GitHub for version control
    ->LeetCode for DSA practice
    ->HackerRank for Java basics
    ->Codeforces after you're comfortable with DSA
*Habits that make a big difference
     ->Code every day, even if it's only 30 minutes.
     ->Don't memorize programs—understand why they work.
     ->Debug your own mistakes before searching for answers.
     ->Read other people's code to learn different approaches.
     ->Build projects alongside studying instead of waiting until you've "finished learning."
*If I were starting from zero today
  ->I would spend about 6 months with a clear plan:
     1.Months 1–2: Core Java + SQL + Git + basic projects.
     2.Months 3–4: DSA (200–300 problems) + Spring Boot + REST APIs.
     3.Months 5–6: Build 3–5 complete projects, learn deployment, and prepare for coding interviews.
*The key is consistency. Many students study a lot for a week and then stop. Writing code regularly, solving problems consistently, and completing projects is what gradually turns a beginner into a confident Java developer.
  If you stay disciplined for six months, you'll have a solid foundation for internships, placements, and entry-level Java developer roles.
